            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mateo Valerio is a product of two worlds. The son of Filipino immigrants, he was raised in Daly City under the weight of his parents\u2019 practical ambitions. His father, a Navy veteran, and his mother, a nurse, saw education as the direct path to stability\u2014a stability they had crossed an ocean to find. They envisioned a future for him in medicine or engineering, but Mateo\u2019s heart was captured by the stark, beautiful images he saw in photography books.\n\nThis artistic calling led him to enroll in the photography program at City College of San Francisco. For two years, he felt alive, documenting the city's hidden corners and vibrant street life through his lens. However, the financial pressure and a growing realization of how precarious an artist\u2019s life could be wore him down. He dropped out, not with a bang, but with a quiet sense of resignation, a turning point that would define his career.\n\nUnwilling to completely abandon his passion, Mateo started volunteering at a small arts non-profit in SoMa. He began by hanging shows and managing the mailing list, but his quiet competence and unflappable nature made him indispensable. He learned logistics, fundraising, and personnel management on the job, slowly climbing the ranks. Over two decades, he built a career not by creating art, but by creating the space for others to do so. Now, as Operations Director, he is the sturdy backbone of the organization, the one who ensures the lights stay on and the art stays on the walls.\n\nAt 48, Mateo\u2019s life has a comfortable rhythm. He lives alone in a rent-controlled apartment in the Mission District, its walls adorned with pieces from artists he\u2019s championed. His daily 2.8-mile bike commute is a cherished ritual, a moving meditation through the city he loves. Though a long-term relationship ended five years ago, his social life remains rich, woven into the fabric of gallery openings and artist talks.\n\nHis dream is no longer to be the one behind the camera. Instead, he aspires to secure a major endowment for his non-profit, ensuring its legacy. Privately, he hopes to one day travel to the Philippines, to photograph the province his parents left behind, this time purely for himself, finally uniting the two worlds he has always navigated."
